Nel corso del XX secolo gli archeologi si sono imbattuti casualmente nella più antica giara di vino mai rinvenuta. Nel 1996, infatti, una missione archeologica statunitense, proveniente dall'Università della Pennsylvania e diretta da Mary Voigt, ha scoperto nel villaggio neolitico di Hajji Firuz Tepe, nella parte settentrionale dell'Iran, una giara di terracotta, della capacità di 9 litri, contenente una sostanza secca proveniente da grappoli d'uva. La notizia, riferita da Corriere Scienza del 15 ottobre 2002, aggiunge che i reperti rinvenuti risalgono al 5100 a.C., quindi a 7000 anni fa, ma gli specialisti affermano che il vino è stato prodotto per la prima volta, forse casualmente, tra 9 000 e 10 000 anni fa nella zona del Caucaso. Sembra infatti che il primo vino sia stato prodotto del tutto per caso (come è avvenuto per il pane lievitato) per la fermentazione accidentale di uva dimenticata in un recipiente.

La birra è una delle bevande più antiche prodotte dall'uomo, probabilmente databile al settimo millennio a.C., registrata nella storia scritta dell'antico Egitto e della Mesopotamia[4]. La prima testimonianza chimica nota è datata intorno al 3500-3100 a.C.[5]. Poiché quasi qualsiasi sostanza contenente carboidrati, come ad esempio zucchero e amido, può andare naturalmente incontro a fermentazione, è probabile che bevande simili alla birra siano state inventate l'una indipendentemente dall'altra da diverse culture in ogni parte del mondo. È stato sostenuto che l'invenzione del pane e della birra sia stata responsabile della capacità dell'uomo di sviluppare tecnologie e di diventare sedentario, formando delle civiltà stabili.[6][7][8].

Raoul Wallenberg-skulpturen i Ångfärjeparken i Helsingborg har vandaliserats. Skadegörelsen upptäcktes i samband med att ett nytt minnesmärke på platsen ska invigas.

I fredags högtidlighölls minnet av Förintelsen över hela världen. Under söndagen skulle fem citat inhuggna i sten invigas vid Raoul Wallenbergs minnesplats. Stenarna ska minna om de båtar med flyktingar som anlände här och på andra platser längs kusten under andra världskriget. På platsen finns redan en skulptur med Raoul Wallenbergs portfölj.

Någon har nu hällt vit färg över hela skulpturen.

– Det är bara förskräckligt tråkigt. Det känns helt meningslöst att det finns sådana krafter i vår närhet, säger Gideon Beil från judiska församlingen som skulle inviga en ny del av minnesplatsen vid kajen i Helsingborg.

Förstärkt bevakning
Polisen beslutade under söndagen att ha en förstärkt bevakning av platsen.

– Vi rubricerar det hela som skadegörelse med hatbrottsmotiv, säger Sara Andersson, presstalesperson vid polisen.

– Att man inte har lärt sig av historien. Det här är ju tanken att vi inte ska glömma, och det här kommer vi inte heller att glömma, säger Gideon Beil när han tittar på den vandaliserade skulpturen.

>>177219421
The default method of getting to school is taking one of the publicly funded buses, which alter their routes every year to tailor to where the young kids are.
If a kid's parents aren't home in the morning (which is unlikely because kids are rarely out of the house later than 8am), then they'll probably be given a key and charged with locking the door. It's also common for parents to coordinate with neighbors (e.g., other families, retirees) to see the kids off to the bus on particular days.

It's pretty common for a kid to come home to an empty house that he has to unlock. The term "latch-key kid" was invented in the 1980s to describe the type of child who comes home to any empty house if mom has a full-time job. There were very noticeable, negative social effects of having kids spend a lot of time alone and unsupervised, so it's become a taboo to let your kid (even teenager) just hang out at home alone all afternoon. Even though it's still common, it's considered bad.

Which is why daycare and babysitting is so common for young kids and why the average high schooler is put in multiple after-school activities, which means he'll be out of the house from like 7am until 5pm.

Ah, right, I wanted to answer questions from the dead thread if everything else in this one was answered when I was asleep:
>>177186899
>Why do russian alsways translate anglo names that start with H as starting with Г, when the just as easily translate with Х?
Not always, that is an old tradition that was phased out in XX century in favor of Х, in modern English loanwords and transliterations Х is used exclusively. Its origin is murky but is probably related to Ukrainian г [ɦ] which is, on one hand, is the closest equivalent there for [h], on other hand, corresponds in Russian to г. My hypothesis is that this transliteration was coined during first influx of Western learned loanwords in XVII century (notice how h = г is used for Greco-Roman international vocabulary too), which happened after Russia reclaimed Left Bank Ukraine and local church brought Western (Polish) academics, with transliteration already tailored by local language.

>>177187148
>Related question, why do they transliterate L as ль, for example in фильм, фильтp, гильзa?
Same reason, Polish l is soft and is used for Western loanwords there, so all loanwords started being transliterated with ль, which was additionally reinforced by huge influence of French on Russian nobility in XIX century. This was phased out in Soviet times too, modern English loanwords are hard л only.

>What word is most common, and what are the usage differences?
>зeмлeдeлeц
>кpecтьянин
>фepмep
Зeмлeдeлeц - "land-tiller", can be used for anyone directly working in agriculture (not including husbandry) but it's a literary word.
Кpecтьянин - "peasant", a historical term so to say
Фepмep - owner of a private market-oriented agricultural enterprise (personal, as opposed to LLCs and other collective property holding forms)
>кoлхoзник is a word too
Simply and only "kolkhoz worker"

Japanese people still carry around a paper booklet that they have to insert into the ATM, on which then the machine will print your last few transactions as well
Online service or an app for that? Or at least send the list of transactions per email? Nope, you have to carry that booklet

No wonder those gigabanks are barely profitable

Lüneburg district
Amt Neuhaus

Amt Neuhaus is an odd shitter. Historically and today it's part of Lower Saxony but during the Cold War it belonged to East Germany. After the tragic fall of the German Reich, Amt Neuhaus became part of the British occupation zone. However, the municipality is located on the right bank of the Elbe river without any bridges connecting it with the rest of Lower Saxony and the Bong zone, making it a practical exclave. For practical purposes the Bongs ceded the territory to the Soviets (RIP).
In 1993, Amt Neuhaus was given to Lower Saxony again, making it the only territory transfer between Eastern and Western Germany after their reunification.

>>177193263
Depends on the country. Cemeteries in Northern and Central Europe are usually open 24/7. Southern Europe is more difficult; cemeteries in Italy or Spain for instance tend to be built like small fortresses with high walls and the gates are often closed at night, particulaly on the densily populated coast. It's easier to find an open cemetery in the rural interior. Occasionally I just sleep in front of the gates.
Orthodox countries also sometimes close their cemeteries for the night.

>>177214815
I’ve lived in Bali for the past 14 years. I grew up there, and I consider it my home.

During this time, the island has undergone a huge and rapid transformation, mostly due to the urbanisation and commercialisation that has been a byproduct of the ever-growing tourism industry. While many Balinese surely benefit economically from this development, their quality of life has decreased dramatically as a result of pollution, toxic western lifestyles, traffic, disintegration of traditional communal networks, consumerism and a constellation of other factors.

Many parts of Bali are indeed a “tourist trap”, in the sense that you will not get a genuine experience of the more cultural, traditional, and nuanced aspects of the “real” Bali. They may be beautiful, and fun, but they could just as well be in Ibiza, or Cancun. These area are part of a “global village”, an attempt to cater to wealthier tourists - some of the most sophisticated consumers on the planet - in an “exotic” location. There is very little that is genuinely “Balinese” about them, except some small elements that manage to survive.

That being said, these areas are primarily (thankfully) concentrated in a rather small part of the island. Much of the territory has not yet been polluted and invaded by tourism development. The problem is that this is a Catch 22 situation. Tourists that are disillusioned with the mainstream spots adventure further out. Word gets out (and spreads quickly due to social media and the internet) about this “secret” waterfall/beach/cave etc. and before you know it, what used to be a “secret” gem is flooded with tourists.

The Balinese are now forced to rely on an industry they do not have a say in, and the development of which they weren’t consulted on.
